full_text: @cuducos Erm, it was, and in many cases it‚Äôs totally fine, but in some cases it‚Äôs not, for example Facebook should not have moved fast, breaking social interaction forever
@dudadornelles Thanks! I‚Äôm thinking that failing fast was a good strategy as well
@cv Yes, that‚Äôs the test I added later, but didn‚Äôt thought about them while developing :/

@fmobus @jlueiza Like a transaction waiting to be commited? That‚Äôs a very cool idea, I think the hard part is to get a big distributed system and all the scheduled jobs running with this fork of the universe to see the real impact of this change

@luizfar Oh yeah! I never stopped validating on prod after that certain project, and I push people to do that as well because it‚Äôs common to ‚Äúmerge and forget‚Äù

This incremental idea is a nice one, I‚Äôll always keep in mind for big changes like this

@glauco There is another surprising theory by a friend: if instead of having all this measures, if we had no tests, no reviews, nothing, maybe we wouldn‚Äôt have our confidence in the process so high, and would have paid more attention to a mistake like that while coding, what you think?
@glauco Wow I didn‚Äôt knew about that, let me check it out!

@glauco Yes, I added a test case just like that after the fact so it doesn't happen again, but how could I be forced to check this case beforehand? I thought about having strict types but even so there are other use cases of deleting only using X, so it could happen anyway

@benjaconb How would it help? TDD, BDD, testing after, QA, you could still remember to test that key X is not there (like we did), but forget to test that existing Y keys remain in place (like we forgot)
@jlueiza Hahahaha my thing was totally far from that, not my fault this time :P

@glauco I knew the table keys, just forgot to add to the condition. Yeah I think I will not forget to check this again in a next time, but my point is what else may I be missing next time? What other black swans are hidden out that? Is it possible to prevent or reduce them?
@jlueiza We did do a manual full run of the script in dev environment, but fun story: I did not notice the extra zero, from 120000 to 1200000 the number of deleted rows seemed fine to me

@benjaconb It would not, this code specifically had 100% test coverage, because of TDD we only write code if there is a failing test

But I cannot predict what I failed to test

The code was built using TDD, during pair programming, went through code review, had some refactorings, you know the good practices. I missed it, my pair missed it, the the tests missed it, the reviewers missed it.

How could we have prevented that?

Now data is restored and it‚Äôs all fine, but question is: how could we have prevented that?

üëá

We had a bug in production: a script, which gets data from table A, apply some rules, then syncs with table B. Problem is, this table uses 2 keys: X and Y, and when doing a batch delete we forgot to provide Y, causing it to delete 1.2M rows instead of 120k

@chrisalbon wow it makes so much sense now! Thank you!
